{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"af4ef258-e48f-40ad-bec0-b6d37acd6817","content":"Two things change when moving to xUnit v3 + MTP:\n\n### 1. `&` → `&` (or use parentheses)\nThe VSTest `&` operator becomes **`&`** in MTP's `--filter`. You can also write it with parentheses for clarity.\n\n### 2. `Category` trait → `Category` (same name, but syntax changes)\nIn MTP, traits are filtered with the **`Category`** property directly (not `Trait`). The `~` (contains) operator is replaced by **`=`** for exact match, or you keep `~` if you truly need substring matching.\n\n### Translated command\n\n```bash\n# Old (VSTest / xUnit v2):\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n\n# New (MTP / xUnit v3):\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests and Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n**Key differences:**\n| VSTest (v2) | MTP (v3) |\n|---|---|\n| `&` | `and` |\n| `\\|` | `or` |\n| `!` | `not` |\n\nThe `FullyQualifiedName~` (contains) syntax still works in MTP. The `Category=Smoke` trait filter also carries over since xUnit v3 maps `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]` to the MTP `Category` property automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9d16dfea-eede-440f-bd40-3c69d189d2e5","outputTokens":352,"requestId":"703E:1B693D:DAB800B:F107CA7:69F2A98C"},"id":"b8169253-d097-404f-9f15-f1865fe66bda","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:00:07.435Z","parentId":"a10edf62-d134-42c5-84fa-6a8b50e16fd5"}
